			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Ultimately, it's always about balancing time. All systems, regardless of whether it's scanline-based or framebuffer-based takes a certain amount of time to blit a certain number of pixels. In a framebuffer-based system, that affects the total number of polygons you can have in a scene, but you can make the tradeoff of dropping the total FPS in exchange for drawing more total things.<br /><br />A tile-based system (not a quad-based system, mind) doesn't give the programmers the ability to make that exchange: there's no framebuffer, and so you only have the time of one scanline to figure out what you're drawing on that scanline. So for the NES you just always get 25% overdraw, because that's how the hardware was designed. This amount of overdraw is a fundamental property when the silicon is designed, and although it could be made arbitrarily huge, there's no point in wasting silicon on something that'll never be used.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
						<tr valign="middle">
							<td class="gensmall" align="right">
							
